Step 1: Configure Git globally

Before working with Git, we must tell Git who we are. This information is attached to every commit we make.
```
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
```

To verify the configuration:
```
git config --global --list
```

Step 2: Create the project directory

We create a new folder named inventory_system which will hold the entire project.
```
mkdir inventory_system
cd inventory_system
```

Step 3: Initialize Git repository

This step turns the project folder into a Git repository so that all changes can be tracked using version control.
```
git init
```

Step 4: Initialize Node.js project using npm

npm init creates a package.json file, which stores metadata, dependencies, and scripts for the Node.js project.
```
npm init -y
```
The -y flag accepts default values automatically.

Step 5: Create required project folders

We create separate folders to organize code, logs, and configuration files.

```
mkdir src
mkdir logs
mkdir config
```

src → application source code

logs → application logs

config → configuration files



Step 6: Create the entry file (index.js)

This file will act as the starting point of the Node.js application.

```
touch src/index.js
```
Add a startup message in the index.js:
```
echo "console.log('Inventory System starting...');" > src/index.js
```

Step 7: Create .gitignore file

We use .gitignore to prevent unnecessary files from being tracked by Git. The node_modules folder should never be committed.
```
touch .gitignore
echo "node_modules/" > .gitignore
```

Step 8: First commit – Initial project setup

This commit saves the initial structure of the project.
```
git add .
git commit -m "Initial project with this message"
```

Step 9: Display compact commit history

This command shows a concise, readable commit history.
```
git log --oneline --graph --decorate
```